{{NCAATeamFootballSeason |Year=2008 |Team= Marshall Thundering Herd |Image= Marshall University Bar M logo.svg |ImageSize= |Conference= Conference USA |Division = East |ShortConference= C-USA |Record= 4â8 |ConfRecord= 3â5 |HeadCoach= [[Mark Snyder]] |OffCoach= John Shannon |DefCoach= [[Rick Minter]] |OScheme= |DScheme= 3-4 |StadiumArena= [[Joan C. Edwards Stadium]] |Champion= |BowlTourney= |BowlTourneyResult= }} {{2008 Conference USA football standings}} The '''2008 Marshall Thundering Herd football team''' represented [[Marshall University]] in [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] [[Division I (NCAA)#Football Bowl Subdivision|Football Bowl Subdivision]] (FBS) [[college football]] during the [[2008 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2008 season]]. Marshall competed as a member of the East Division of [[Conference USA]], and played their home games at [[Joan C. Edwards Stadium]]. The Thundering Herd were led by fourth-year head coach [[Mark Snyder]]. Marshall finished the season with a 4â8 record (3â5).<ref>[http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_game_by_game.php?coachid=3790&year=2008 Marshall 2008], College Football Data Warehouse, retrieved June 29, 2009. [http://www.webcitation.org/5iUHCmqso Archived] 2009-07-23.</ref>
Before the season, ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' ranked Marshall the 115th team in the FBS (out of 120) and predicted they would finish with a 1â11 record. Against 11th-ranked [[2008 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]], the Herd led 14â0 in the second quarter, but gave up 51 [[unanswered points]] in the remainder of the game. Later in the season, Marshall upset [[2008 Houston Cougars football team|Houston]], 37â23, after having led 37â9 earlier in the final period. The following week, they lost in [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] to favorite [[2008 East Carolina Pirates football team|East Carolina]] by a [[Field goal (football)|field goal]], 19â16. Marshall held [[2008 Rice Owls football team|Rice]] quarterback [[Chase Clement]] to 84 passing yards in the first half, which was tied at 7, but went on to lose, 35â10. In the season closer, they proved competitive for eventual [[2008 Conference USA Championship Game|Conference USA runners-up]] [[2008 Tulsa Golden Hurricane football team|Tulsa]].<ref name=steele>''[[Phil Steele's]] 2009 College Football Preview'', vol. 15, p. 210, 2009.</ref>
